GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 1
SENATE BILL 386
Short Title: Whiz Kids/Slow Pokes Voter Registration. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Meyer and Smith (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
March 25, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ENSURE PROCRASTINATORS THEIR RIGHT TO VOTE BY
3 ESTABLISHING SAME-DAY REGISTRATION ON ELECTION DAY AND TO
4 ENGAGE OVERACHIEVING TEENAGERS IN VOTING BY RECODIFYING THE
5 PROGRAM TO PREREGISTER INDIVIDUALS SIXTEEN AND SEVENTEEN YEARS
6 OF AGE.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8
9 PART I. SAME-DAY VOTER REGISTRATION ON ELECTION DAY
10 SECTION 1.1. G.S. 163-82.6B reads as rewritten:
11 "§ 163-82.6B. Same-day registration.
12 (a) Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, an individual who is qualified
13 to register to vote may register in person and then vote in the person's county of residence on
14 election day or at an early voting site in the individual's county of residence during the period for
15 early voting provided under Part 5 of Article 14A of this Chapter.
16 (b) To register and vote under this section, an individual shall do all of the following:
17 (1) Complete a voter registration application form as prescribed in G.S. 163-82.4.
18 (2) Provide proof of residence by presenting a HAVA document listing the
19 individual's current name and residence address.
20 (3) Present photo identification in accordance with G.S. 163-166.16.
21 (c) An applicant who registers under this section shall vote a retrievable ballot as
22 provided in G.S. 163-166.45 immediately after submitting the voter registration application form.
23 If a person declines to vote immediately, the registration shall be processed, and the person may
24 later vote at an early voting site under this section in the same election if the early voting period
25 has not closed.
26 (d) Within two business days of the individual's registration under this section, the county
27 board of elections in conjunction with the State Board shall verify the North Carolina drivers
28 license or social security number in accordance with G.S. 163-82.12, update the statewide
29 registration database, search for possible duplicate registrations, and proceed under
30 G.S. 163-82.7 to verify the applicant's address. The applicant's vote shall be counted unless the
31 county board determines that the applicant is not qualified to vote in accordance with this
32 Chapter. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Chapter, if the Postal Service returns the
33 first notice required under G.S. 163-82.7(c) as undeliverable before the close of business on the
34 business day before canvass, the county board shall not register the applicant and shall retrieve
35 the applicant's ballot and remove that ballot's votes from the official count.
*S386-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (e) For purposes of this section, a "HAVA document" is any of the following that shows
2 the name and address of the individual:
3 (1) A current utility bill.
4 (2) A current bank statement.
5 (3) A current government check.
6 (4) A current paycheck.
7 (5) Another current government document.
8 (6) A current document issued from the institution who issued the photo
9 identification shown by the voter pursuant to G.S. 163-166.16.
10 (f) Any person who will become qualified by age to register and vote in the general
11 election for which a partisan or nonpartisan primary is held, even though not so qualified by the
12 date of the primary, may register for the primary and general election prior to the primary and
13 then vote in the primary and general election after being registered in accordance with the
14 provisions of this section."
15 SECTION 1.2. G.S. 163-59 reads as rewritten:
16 "§ 163-59. Right to participate or vote in party primary.
17 No person shall be entitled to vote or otherwise participate in the primary election of any
18 political party unless that person complies with all of the following:
19 (1) Is a registered voter.
20 (2) Has declared and has had recorded on the registration book or record the fact
21 that the voter affiliates with the political party in whose primary the voter
22 proposes to vote or participate.
23 (3) Is in good faith a member of that party.
24 Notwithstanding the previous paragraph, any unaffiliated voter who is authorized under
25 G.S. 163-119 may also vote in the primary if the voter is otherwise eligible to vote in that primary
26 except for subdivisions (2) and (3) of the previous paragraph.
27 Any person who will become qualified by age to register and vote in the general election for
28 which the primary is held, even though not so qualified by the date of the primary, shall be
29 entitled to register for the primary and general election prior to the primary and then to vote in
30 the primary after being registered. Such person may register not earlier than 60 days nor later
31 than the last day for making application to register under G.S. 163-82.6(d) prior to the primary.
32 In addition, persons who will become qualified by age to register and vote in the general election
33 for which the primary is held, who do not register during the special period may register to vote
34 after such period as if they were qualified on the basis of age, but until they are qualified by age
35 to vote, they may vote only in primary elections. The person also may register and vote in the
36 primary and general election pursuant to G.S. 163-82.6B."
37 SECTION 1.3. G.S. 163-82.6(d) reads as rewritten:
38 "(d) Registration Deadlines for a Primary or Election. – In Except as provided in
39 G.S. 163-82.6B, in order to be valid for a primary or election, the form:
40 (1) If submitted by mail, must be postmarked at least 25 days before the primary
41 or election, except that any mailed application on which the postmark is
42 missing or unclear is validly submitted if received in the mail not later than 20
43 days before the primary or election,
44 (2) If submitted in person, by facsimile transmission, or by transmission of a
45 scanned document, must be received by the county board of elections by a
46 time established by that board, but no earlier than 5:00 P.M., on the
47 twenty-fifth day before the primary or election,
48 (3) If submitted through a delegatee who violates the duty set forth in subsection
49 (a) of this section, must be signed by the applicant and given to the delegatee
50 not later than 25 days before the primary or election, except as provided in
51 subsection (f) of this section."
