1 SECTION 1.4. G.S. 163-166.12(d), as amended by Section 3A.4(c) of S.L. 2024-57,
2 reads as rewritten:
3 "(d) Voting When Identification Numbers Do Not Match. – Regardless of whether an
4 individual has registered by mail or by another method, if the individual has provided with the
5 registration form a drivers license number or last four digits of a Social Security number but the
6 computer validation of the number as required by G.S. 163-82.12 did not result in a match, and
7 the number has not been otherwise validated by the county board, in the first election in which
8 the individual votes that individual shall submit with the ballot the form of identification
9 described in subsection (a) or subsection (b) of this section, depending upon whether the ballot
10 is voted in person or absentee. If that identification is provided no later than 12:00 P.M. on the
11 third business day after the election and the county board does not determine that the individual
12 is otherwise ineligible to vote a ballot, the failure of identification numbers to match shall not
13 prevent that individual from registering to vote and having that individual's vote counted. If the
14 individual registers and votes under G.S. 163-82.6B, the identification documents required in
15 that section, rather than those described in subsection (a) or (b) of this section, apply."
16 SECTION 1.5. G.S. 163-283 reads as rewritten:
17 "§ 163-283. Right to participate or vote in party primary.
18 No person shall be entitled to vote or otherwise participate in the primary election of any
19 political party unless that person complies with all of the following:
20 (1) Is a registered voter.
21 (2) Has declared and has had recorded on the registration book or record the fact
22 that the voter affiliates with the political party in whose primary the voter
23 proposes to vote or participate.
24 (3) Is in good faith a member of that party.
25 Notwithstanding the previous paragraph, any unaffiliated voter who is authorized under
26 G.S. 163-119 may also vote in the primary if the voter is otherwise eligible to vote in that primary
27 except for subdivisions (2) and (3) of the previous paragraph.
28 Any person who will become qualified by age to register and vote in the general election for
29 which the primary is held, even though not so qualified by the date of the primary election, shall
30 be entitled to register while the registration books are open during the regular registration period
31 prior to the primary and then to vote in the primary after being registered, provided however,
32 under full-time and permanent registration, such an individual may register not earlier than 60
33 days nor later than the last day for making application to register under G.S. 163-82.6(d) prior to
34 the primary. In addition, persons who will become qualified by age to register and vote in the
35 general election for which the primary is held, who do not register during the special period may
36 register to vote after such period as if they were qualified on the basis of age, but until they are
37 qualified by age to vote, they may vote only in primary elections. The person also may register
38 and vote in the primary and general election pursuant to G.S. 163-82.6B."
39 SECTION 1.6. G.S. 163-283.1 reads as rewritten:
40 "§ 163-283.1. Voting in nonpartisan primary.
41 Any person who will become qualified by age to register and vote in the general election for
42 which a nonpartisan primary is held, even though not so qualified by the date of the primary,
43 shall be entitled to register for the primary and general election prior to the primary and then to
44 vote in the primary after being registered. Such a person may register not earlier than 60 days nor
45 later than the last day for making application to register under G.S. 163-82.6(d) prior to the
46 primary. The person also may register and vote in the primary and general election pursuant to
47 G.S. 163-82.6B."
48
49 PART II. PREREGISTRATION
50 SECTION 2.1. G.S. 163-82.1 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
Senate Bill 386-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "(d) Preregistration. – A person who is at least 16 years of age but will not be 18 years of
2 age by the date of the next election and who is otherwise qualified to register may preregister to
3 vote and shall be automatically registered upon reaching the age of eligibility following
4 verification of the person's qualifications and address in accordance with G.S. 163-82.7."
5 SECTION 2.2. G.S. 163-82.3(a) is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
6 "(5) Preregister to vote."
7 SECTION 2.3. G.S. 163-82.4(e)(2) reads as rewritten:
8 "(2) The following question questions and statement:
9 a. "Will you be 18 years of age on or before election day?" and boxes for
10 the applicant to check to indicate whether the applicant will be 18
11 years of age or older on election day.
12 b. "Are you at least 16 years of age and understand that you must be 18
13 years of age on or before election day to vote?" and boxes for the
14 applicant to check to indicate whether the applicant is at least 16 years
15 of age and understands that the applicant must be at least 18 years of
16 age or older by election day to vote.
17 c. "If you checked "no' in response to this question, both of these
18 questions, do not submit this form.""
19 SECTION 2.4. G.S. 163-82.19(a) reads as rewritten:
20 "(a) Voter Registration at Drivers License Offices. – The Division of Motor Vehicles
21 shall, pursuant to the rules adopted by the State Board of Elections, modify its forms so that any
22 eligible person who applies for original issuance, renewal or correction of a drivers license, or
23 special identification card issued under G.S. 20-37.7 may, on a part of the form, complete an
24 application to register to vote, or to update the voter's registration if the voter has changed his or
25 her address or moved from one precinct to another or from one county to another. another, or to
26 preregister to vote. The person taking the application shall ask if the applicant is a citizen of the
27 United States. If the applicant states that the applicant is not a citizen of the United States, or
28 declines to answer the question, the person taking the application shall inform the applicant that
29 it is a felony for a person who is not a citizen of the United States to apply to register to vote. The
30 application shall state in clear language the penalty for violation of this section. The necessary
31 forms shall be prescribed by the State Board of Elections. The form must ask for the previous
32 voter registration address of the voter, if any. If a previous address is listed, and it is not in the
33 county of residence of the applicant, the appropriate county board of elections shall treat the
34 application as an authorization to cancel the previous registration and also process it as such
35 under the procedures of G.S. 163-82.9. If a previous address is listed and that address is in the
36 county where the voter applies to register, the application shall be processed as if it had been
37 submitted under G.S. 163-82.9.
38 Registration shall become effective as provided in G.S. 163-82.7. Applications to register to
39 vote accepted at a drivers license office under this section until the deadline established in
40 G.S. 163-82.6(d)(2) shall be treated as timely made for an election, and no person who completes
41 an application at that drivers license office shall be denied the vote in that election for failure to
42 apply earlier than that deadline.
43 All applications shall be forwarded by the Department of Transportation to the appropriate
44 board of elections not later than five business days after the date of acceptance, according to rules
45 which shall be promulgated by the State Board of Elections. Those rules shall provide for a
46 paperless, instant, electronic transfer of applications to the appropriate board of elections. All
47 applications for preregistration shall be forwarded to the State Board of Elections."
48 SECTION 2.5. G.S. 163-82.20 reads as rewritten:
49 "§ 163-82.20. Voter registration at other public agencies.
50 …
