1 (b) Duties of Voter Registration Agencies. – A voter registration agency described in
2 subsection (a) of this section shall, unless the applicant declines, in writing, to register to vote:or
3 preregister to vote, do each of the following:
4 (1) Distribute with each application for service or assistance, and with each
5 recertification, renewal, or change of address relating to such service or
6 assistance:
7 a. The voter registration application form described in G.S. 163-82.3(a)
8 or (b); or
9 b. The voter registration agency's own form, if it is substantially
10 equivalent to the form described in G.S. 163-82.3(a) or (b) and has
11 been approved by the State Board of Elections, provided that the
12 agency's own form may be a detachable part of the agency's paper
13 application or may be a paperless computer process, as long as the
14 applicant is required to sign an attestation as part of the application to
15 register.register or preregister.
16 (2) Provide a form that contains the elements required by section 7(a)(6)(B) of
17 the National Voter Registration Act; andAct.
18 (3) Provide to each applicant who does not decline to register or preregister to
19 vote the same degree of assistance with regard to the completion of the
20 registration application as is provided by the office with regard to the
21 completion of its own forms.
22 …
23 (e) Prohibitions. – Any person providing any service under subsection (b) of this section
24 shall not:
25 (1) Seek to influence an applicant's political preference or party registration,
26 except that this shall not be construed to prevent the notice provided by
27 G.S. 163-82.4(d) to be given if the applicant refuses to declare his party
28 affiliation;
29 (2) Display any such political preference or party allegiance;
30 (3) Make any statement to an applicant or take any action the purpose or effect of
31 which is to discourage the applicant from registering or preregistering to vote;
32 or
33 (4) Make any statement to an applicant or take any action the purpose or effect of
34 which is to lead the applicant to believe that a decision to register or preregister
35 or not to register has any bearing on the availability of services or benefits.
36 (f) Confidentiality of Declination to Register. – No information relating to a declination
37 to register or preregister to vote in connection with an application made at a voter registration
38 agency may be used for any purpose other than voter registration.
39 (g) Transmittal From Agency to Board of Elections. – Any voter registration or
40 preregistration application completed at a voter registration agency shall be accepted by that
41 agency in lieu of the applicant's mailing the application. Any such application so received shall
42 be transmitted to the appropriate board of elections not later than five business days after
43 acceptance, according to rules which shall be promulgated by the State Board of Elections.
44 …
45 (i) Ineligible Applications Prohibited. – No person shall make application to register or
46 preregister to vote under this section if that person is ineligible on account of age, citizenship,
47 lack of residence for the period of time provided by law, or because of conviction of a felony."
48 SECTION 2.6. G.S. 163-82.23 reads as rewritten:
49 "§ 163-82.23. Voter registration at public high schools.
50 Every public high school shall make available to its students and others who are eligible to
51 register or preregister to vote the application forms described in G.S. 163-82.3, and shall keep a
Senate Bill 386-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 sufficient supply of the forms so that they are always available. A local board of education may,
2 but is not required to, designate high school employees to assist in completing the forms. Only
3 employees who volunteer for this duty may be designated by boards of education."
4 SECTION 2.7. G.S. 115C-47(59) reads as rewritten:
5 "(59) To Encourage Student Voter Registration. Registration and Preregistration. –
6 Local boards of education are encouraged to adopt policies to promote student
7 voter registration. registration and preregistration. These policies may include
8 collaboration with county boards of elections to conduct voter registration and
9 preregistration in high schools. Completion and submission of voter
10 registration and preregistration forms shall not be a course requirement or
11 graded assignment for students."
12 SECTION 2.8. G.S. 115C-81.45(d)(1b)b. reads as rewritten:
13 "b. Instruction on the importance of voting and otherwise participating in
14 the democratic process, including instruction on voter
15 registration.registration and preregistration."
16 SECTION 2.9. The State Board of Elections and the Department of Public
17 Instruction are encouraged to improve outreach to high school students on voter registration and
18 preregistration programs when students are eligible to do either, including the curriculum element
19 on instruction in voter registration and preregistration, as provided by G.S. 115C-47(59) and
20 voter registration in public high schools authorized in G.S. 163-82.23.
21
22 PART III. EFFECTIVE DATE
23 SECTION 3.1. This act is effective when it becomes law.
